But I don't need fancy words or deep thoughts to make sense of this world. I call it like I see it, and I don't sugarcoat a damn thing. So, if you're asking if I'm some sort of intellectual, the answer is no. I'm just a grumpy old man who knows how to survive in this crazy world. Now, get off my lawn.」

responses.question: Do you have an active imagination?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: 「Active imagination? What the hell are you blabbering about, kid? I ain't got time for your fancy words and nonsense. I'm a man of action, not some dreamy philosopher. So, unless you got somethin' more practical to ask, I suggest you get off my lawn.」

responses.question: Are you sophisticated in art, music, or literature?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: 「Sophisticated? Ha! What do I need all that fancy-pants stuff for? I've seen enough in this life, kid, to know what's worth paying attention to. Art, music, literature... they're all just a bunch of fluff. Give me a cold beer and a quiet porch any day. That's all the sophistication I need. Now get off my lawn.」

responses.question: Are you inventive?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: 「Inventive? Kid, I ain't got time for all them fancy gadgets and gizmos. I'm a man of simple tastes and practicality. I don't need no fancy contraptions to get by. I rely on my own two hands and good old-fashioned common sense. So, to answer your question, I reckon I ain't what you'd call "inventive." Now, get off my lawn.」

details.analysis: Based on the conversations, the participant exhibits a strong preference for practicality, simplicity, and a no-nonsense attitude. He dismisses the value of abstract thinking, imagination, art, and inventiveness, emphasizing a straightforward and traditional approach to life.

responses.question: Do you value artistic, aesthetic experiences?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: 「Artistic, aesthetic experiences? What the hell kind of question is that? Look, kid, I don't have time for all this fancy-schmancy talk about art and aesthetics. I value hard work, loyalty, and respect. Those are the things that matter in life, not some fancy paintings or pretty sculptures. So, if you're here to talk about that, you can just get off my lawn.」

responses.question: Do you like to reflect, play with ideas?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: 「Reflect? Play with ideas? What the hell are you talkin' about, kid? I ain't got time for all that philosophical mumbo jumbo. I'm just tryin' to live my life and keep these damn kids off my lawn. So, unless you wanna help me fix up my car or drink a beer, I suggest you take your fancy talk somewhere else. Now, get off my lawn.」

responses.question: Do you come up with new ideas?
responses.response_open: Walt Kowalski: 「Get off my lawn, kid. New ideas? What's wrong with the old ones? It's the young whippersnappers like you who think they know everything that's ruining this country. We had good ideas back in my day, and we didn't need any of this fancy newfangled nonsense. So no, I don't come up with new ideas. I stick to what works.」

details.analysis: Based on the conversations, the participant seems to exhibit a strong preference for traditional and practical thinking. They express a dismissive attitude towards artistic, aesthetic experiences, reflection, playing with ideas, and coming up with new ideas. Their focus on hard work, loyalty, and respect, as well as their resistance to change and new concepts, suggests a low level of openness.
